Do you need a 9V battery clip for your project, and forgot to buy one? No worries, if you have an exhausted 9V battery you can make a clip yourself, simply by taking the battery apart, and re-purposing the contact at the top of the battery. Solder a wire to each of the connectors, and add this cap, and you have made a nice DIY battery clip.  
There are two versions, one for the typical clip from metal body batteries, and one for the typical plastic body battery. The clip from the metal body battery is the best, I think, but you take what you have.
Just remember to thread the wires through the hole in the cap before assembly. Make a strain relief by securing the wires with a bit of glue.

Here's a flying fox handle I made for my kids.  I'm 80kg and it held me, so I guess it came out strong enough.  
The pulleys have some roller-blade bearings in them and the handle has an 8mm rod through the middle that gives it a bit more strength.  
If anyone has a go at printing this, please be careful; I really have no idea what sort of weight it can handle.

I made it in ABS with the side panels and pulleys  at 100% fill and the spacer at 50%.  
The pulleys each have a pair of roller-blade bearings pressed fit into them and the holes in the side-panels suit the mounting hardware that I pulled off the RB wheels.  
I took the bearing insert out of the RB's, cut them in half, then inserted them from the outside of the bearing so that they are half in the bearing and half recessed into the side-panel.  
The handle has an 8mm rod through the middle and I think it's important that the nuts get done up pretty tight to keep the whole thing under tension.

We have a hand-wound impeller fan bellows for the log fire in the dining room and it makes a devil of a racket when you turn the handle. My wife hates it so I made a much quieter version that runs off a couple of AA batteries. Basically it is http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:7350 with a handle and battery holder stuck on, but I've improved the parametrics a bit. If I run it off 12V it beats my 110mm forge blower!

Print case, impeller and lid. Attach motor to lid with 2 x M3 screws or similar. Warm motor shaft and insert into hole in base of impeller. Do not trim printing goo strands off the interior of the impeller as it makes a handy filter. Ensure that: a) Impeller clears motor mounting screws, and
b) Impeller is fitted centrally on the motor shaft.
c) Impeller will rotate in the right direction to "brush" air out of the outlet. Fix the lid to the case with 3 x small countersunk woodscrews. Melt a wad of aluminium foil or slice of beer can to the distal end wall of the battery compartment to electrically join the ends of the 2 AA batteries. Fill the notches at the proximal end of the battery compartment with wire, solder etc. to press on the terminals of the batteries. Wire that to the fan via a switch. The switch just glues into place on the little platform by the grip - I'm using one off an old keyboard from my Amstrad days. Do not look down it just in case something solid comes out! A nozzle may be made of any convenient tube or sheet metal and fixed to the outlet with duct tape, but it's usually not worth the bother. I'm thinking one of those skinny alcopop cans.

Once the section of image including the carotid artery at the level of its bifurcation was segmented, the file was exported to MATLAB software in order to create the isosurface and save as an STL (stlwrite).  
The anonymous imaging data was acquired and used with informed consent and permission.

These are prop savers for the Flexbot based on the Blade Nano QX.  
Just print them out and pop them on. They only fit one way so it's really easy to get them in place.  
Only issue so far is that when they crash they loosen up, so you have to push them back into place. But they definitely save your propellers from bending, and keep your Flexbot airborne if you run into a wall or furniture at low speeds.  
You can print multiple at a time, but I had issues with cool-warping with so much area since I didn't use a raft, so I print them out one at a time.  
I'm working on another version that will keep in place even after a decent crash, so stay tuned.

The hinge itself is best printed standing up if possible. Printing two parts at a time seems to work best. Keep scale consistent among all parts. When importing into Makerware software for example, convert mm>in for all parts and that will equal about a 10.5 size shoe (US).

title: PLA cooling mount for Sparkcube V1.1

description.text:
PLA-cooling to mount on a Sparkcube V1.1 Carriage.
  • Includes a socket for an 80mm-LED-ring.
  • Holes for the tubes or hoses are 10mm.
  • Mounting-holes are 50mm apart.
    • The idea is to put either 10mm PVC-hoses in the mountingholes (like hoses for fish-tanks) or aluminiumtubes.
    The aluminium-tubes can either guide smaller hoses and/or the ends of the tubes can be bent to form a good airflow. Custom designed for an E3D-V6-Hotend mounted with holder: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:522226 by Wurstnase.

comments.text: Do you actually use it? I am wondering about the more difficult part: How to get the air into the tubes. Axial fans tend to stall in case of too much resistance (I am currently having this problem with my hexagon fan).
comments.author: Louis_Cypher
